A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Other
The mobile market in Czechia is relatively advanced, our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, we still lack the same thing - a virtual operator, who would force classic operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, at times, on Mobile.cz the fact that Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÜ (Techéque des Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, has also confirmed it.
This is why, following the recent failure of the European Commission in the area of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How is it possible to maintain prices in Czechia so high, compared with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we have even three mobile networks and a penetration exceeding 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this connection, Pavel Dvorák, President of the Czech Telecommunications Office (CHT), stated several times that there was no room for another operator in Chequia, made a mess with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network does not appear to have more chance (and, at the present time, he would only find the frequencies difficult).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is just the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable drop in prices, which should therefore also be the reaction of the classic operators.
However, even before the entry of parties such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those we hear today were allowed to be heard in Great Britain.
However, it appears that he was left of the place for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We are no longer obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch, in Poland, of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In six months alone, this operator has succeeded in gaining over 100 thousand customers and becoming the fifth operator of the country.
We add that behind the Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which is also owned by the U:fon in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more specific target group.
In order to be effective, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
In fact, they are relatively high without cost of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is also the case in the world, virtual operators define themselves as low-cost operators - they offer high-market calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMSs at least twice as expensive as its competitors in Great Britain.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, working on an unusual target group can also be a good part of advertising.
In fact, this operator specifically refers to men.
"The real men choose Mobileking - an operator that they like and they can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept could be possible to walk with us as well.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone's spokesman, is undoubtedly: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
It is more than relatively satisfied with the point of view of the provision of services."
In Czech, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czechia, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project successfully, but negotiations in Czechia are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studničková, the spokesman of the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in Czechia were not, in any case, in favour of this idea.
Instead, they tried to do their best so that a potential competitor could not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which wanted to launch a new step to become a real Telephonika competitor in the field of business customers, has not been hiding its intention for a long time to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We have much to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services but also mobile ones.
