The smart car imitates the flight of the bourdon
What would be the best way to develop technologies capable of avoiding a barrier, if this is not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector already in nature?
Like, for example, the one of the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, the bourgeoisies gave the strategic idea of starting with Nissan engineers, to inspire them in the way they had to design the next generation of obstacles.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan built a mini robot vehicle, a bio-robotized control system of type BR23C, which has equipped baby qualities, the ultimate goal is to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
In its flight, each bee is its own space, oval form, which is actually very similar to our secure protection coke - explained at the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of the Department of Research and Development and Public Technology of the brand.
The face-to-face of the bee plays a primary role, since it is possible to see in all directions, in a 300-degree angle.
In order to imitate the functions of the facet eye, engineers have addressed the idea of the laser telemeter.
This identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres before the BR23C, it assesses the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into an escape operation all the time.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movement of the bee, changes immediately the direction of its wheels by turning it into a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
In contrast to any existing system, this avoidance approach is completely instinctively carried out.
"If it hadn't been like this, the mini robot could not respond fast enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must act in an instinctive and instantaneous way, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of protection, a layer which, for the moment, is considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in an eyeline.
In contrast with the bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that have bees to avoid other bees, in our case, we can only use rotational movement, acceleration and slowing as manuals available to the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses the Lithium polymer batteries which are smaller and whose energy concentration is greater, making them live longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is primary, not data processing, and even less storage capacity.
This mechanism must only deal with a few signals coming in second, and respond to those.
It is not necessary to store and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres. Thus, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
We don't need to remember a giga-octets capacity, or even mega-octets.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for instant protection. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will have its entry into the cars produced in series over the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its path.
